em with the formation of a neoliberal European Union and wider capitalist globalizations. Focusing on working classes situated in long-run localized processes of social change, including processes of dispossession and disenfranchisement, this volume investigates how the experiences, histories, and relationships of social class are a necessary ingredient for explaining the re-emergence and dynamics of populist nationalism in both Eastern and Western Europe. Featuring in-depth urban and regional case studies from Romania, Hungary, Serbia, Italy and Scotland this volume reclaims class for anthropological research and lays out a new interdisciplinary agenda for studying identity politics in the intensifying neoliberal conjuncture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aNationalismzEurope. 0aSocial movementszEurope. 0aWorking classzEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBaca, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartha, Eszter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlim, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaje, Florin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilfillan, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalmai, Gábor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalmai, Gábor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKalb, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKalb, Don, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPetrovici, Norbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStacul, Jaro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVetta, Theodora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id